Indeed in some respects, 'tis most true, Gods Commandments are exceeding heavy. There is in them not onely magnum pondus, they are weighty and ponderous; but they are also, magnum onu
                     â€¢â€¦
                  , heavy and burthensome. See the truth of this in three Particulars;

list.item:
1. Take the Law of God at its full height, and pitch of perfection, so it hath a great difficulty in it; yea, in a manner, an impossibility in it to all men since Adam. Never any but the first Adam in his Innocency could have fulfilled it; never any but  the second Adam, our Lord Iesus, did perfectly fulfil it. S. Paul tells us of 
                     ã€ˆ in non-Latin alphabet ã€‰
                  , Rom. viii. an impotencyâ–ª nay an impossibility in the Law, by reason of sin. Indeed, when God first gave the Law, it was sutable to our strength, but sin infeebled us, and so the Law proved impossible to us. Saint Peter tells us, It was a yoke that neither we, nor our fathers could bear, Act. xv. 10. Not onely men in the state of Corruption, but the very Saints in the state of Regeneration, come short of it. Imperfection of grace, cannot attain to perfection of obedience. The Church of God defended this truth against the Pelagians; That the Law  of God in the exactness of it, no meer man did ever fulfil it. There are two Dimensions in the Law;

1. Ob jus dominii; He yields up his life to God, as the Lord of it. No man lives to himself, and no man dies to himself;

                  whether we live, we live to the Lord, whether we die, we die to him; whether therefore we live or die, we are the Lords, Rom. xiv. 7. placed here in our stations. The issues of life belong unto him. We are not Masters of our time, or life. David served


                  his time according to the counsel of God. Old Simeon begs his  dismission.
